Introduction

The tutorial data can be downloaded from:

http://chrisquince.github.io/tutorials/MultivariateStatsTutorial.tar.gz

The tutorial assumes you have unarchived this file and are running R with pwd set to that directory.

We will begin by reading in the 5% OTU table and meta data for the AOA study discussed in the lectures. Note that we transpose OTU matrix:

otus <- read.csv("AllSites_C05.csv",header=TRUE,row.names=1)
otus <- t(otus)
env <- read.csv("Env.csv",header=TRUE,row.names=1)

Load libraries:

library(gplots)
library(ggplot2)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(vegan)
library(GUniFrac)
library(ggdendro)
library(picante)
library(grid)
library(reshape2)
library(DESeq2)

Filter samples with less than 1000 reads:

otus_1e3 <- otus[rowSums(otus) > 1000,]
env_1e3 <- env[rownames(otus_1e3),]

Rarefy species richness:

env_1e3$S_rare <-  rarefy(otus_1e3, 1000, se = FALSE, MARGIN = 1)

Note that we attach the dataframe to make variables visible and then test for correlation between rarefied diversity and pH:

attach(env_1e3)
cor.test(S_rare,pH)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  S_rare and pH
## t = 2.7299, df = 42, p-value = 0.009217
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1032138 0.6142839
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.3881989

Find a positive correlation which is confirmed by plot:

p <- ggplot(data=env_1e3,aes(x=pH,y=S_rare)) + theme_bw() + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + ylab("Rarefied 3% richness") + xlab("pH")
plot(p)
## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is <1000, so using loess. Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

Clustering

Now we will generate a hierarchical clustering of samples:

otus_1e3P <- otus_1e3/rowSums(otus_1e3)

otus_1e3P.dist <- vegdist(otus_1e3P,dist="bray")

otus_1e3P.hclust <- hclust(otus_1e3P.dist,method="ward.D")

ggdendrogram(otus_1e3P.hclust, rotate = FALSE, size = 2)

A clustering is an exploratory form of data analysis, often a heatmap partcularly coupled to clustering is more useful. Here we only cluster the OTUs and order rows by pH to explore relationships between pH and abundance:

crp <- colorRampPalette(c("blue","red","orange","yellow"))(100)
otusPH <- data.frame(otus_1e3P,pH=env_1e3$pH)
otusPH.order <- otusPH[order(env_1e3$pH),]
otusPH.order$pH <- NULL  
otusPH.matrix <- as.matrix(otusPH.order)

heatmap.2 (sqrt(otusPH.matrix ),col=crp,trace="none",Rowv=FALSE,cexCol=0.5,cexRow=0.6)
## Warning in heatmap.2(sqrt(otusPH.matrix), col = crp, trace = "none", Rowv =
## FALSE, : Discrepancy: Rowv is FALSE, while dendrogram is `column'. Omitting
## row dendogram.

otus_1e3P.pca <- rda(otus_1e3P)

Can plot this with inbuilt vegan functions but result is quite ugly:

ordiplot(otus_1e3P.pca,display="sites")

Instead we pull out PC1,PC2 of sites add pH and plot with ggplot2:

pca_df<-scores(otus_1e3P.pca,display=c("sites"))

pca_df<-data.frame(cbind(pca_df,pH=env_1e3$pH))

crp2 <- colorRampPalette(c("red","orange","green","blue","darkblue"))

sc <- scale_colour_gradientn(colours = crp2(100), limits=c(3, 9))

p<-ggplot(data=pca_df,aes(PC1,PC2,colour=pH)) + geom_point(size=3) + sc + theme_bw()

plot(p)

Correspondence analysis

Now lets try correspondence analysis:

otus_1e3P.cca <- cca(otus_1e3P)

cca_df<-scores(otus_1e3P.cca,display=c("sites"))

cca_df<-data.frame(cbind(cca_df,pH=env_1e3$pH))

p<-ggplot(data=cca_df,aes(CA1,CA2,colour=pH)) + geom_point(size=3) + sc + theme_bw()

Now we will biplot species with over 5% of reads on average:

species_df<-data.frame(scores(otus_1e3P.cca,display=c("species")))

species_df_01 <- species_df[colMeans(otus_1e3P) > 0.01,]

species_df_01$Name <- rownames(species_df_01)

species_plot_df <- data.frame(x=species_df_01$CA1,y=species_df_01$CA2,Name=rownames(species_df_01))

p <- p + geom_text(data=species_plot_df,aes(x,y,label=Name),size=3,inherit.aes=F)

plot(p)

Principal coordinates analysis using generalised Unifrac

First we need to read in tree:

tr <- read.tree("RAxML_bestTree.AllSite.tree")

Calculate Unifrac distances:

otus_1e3P.gunifrac <- GUniFrac(otus_1e3P, tr, alpha=c(0, 0.5, 1))$unifracs

Extract weighted Unifrac distances:

otus_1e3P.uf <- otus_1e3P.gunifrac[,,"d_1"]

Perform principle coordinates analysis and plot:

otus_1e3P.cap <- capscale(otus_1e3P.uf ~ 1)

cap_uf_df<-scores(otus_1e3P.cap,display=c("sites"))

cap_uf_df<-data.frame(cbind(cap_uf_df,pH=env_1e3$pH))

p<-ggplot(data=cap_uf_df,aes(MDS1,MDS2,colour=pH)) + geom_point(size=3) + sc + theme_bw()

plot(p)

We will now demonstrate how to add environmental contours to plot.

ordi<-ordisurf(otus_1e3P.nmds,env_1e3$pH,plot = FALSE, bs="ds")

ordi.grid <- ordi$grid #extracts the ordisurf object
str(ordi.grid) #it's a list though - cannot be plotted as is
## List of 3
##  $ x: num [1:31] -4.61 -4.4 -4.18 -3.97 -3.76 ...
##  $ y: num [1:31] -1.452 -1.334 -1.217 -1.1 -0.983 ...
##  $ z: num [1:31, 1:31] NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA ...
ordi.mite <- expand.grid(x = ordi.grid$x, y = ordi.grid$y) #get x and ys
ordi.mite$z <- as.vector(ordi.grid$z) #unravel the matrix for the z scores
ordi.mite.na <- data.frame(na.omit(ordi.mite)) #gets rid of the nas
 
p<-p + stat_contour(data = ordi.mite.na, aes(x = x, y = y, z = z, colour =..level..),positon="identity")

plot(p)

In original, reference cluster study, only pH significant, now find pH, LOI and vegetation*. Redo CCA with these and generate plot:

otus_1e3PR.cca <- cca(otus_1e3P ~ pH + LOI + vegetation,data=env_1e3)

scrs<-scores(otus_1e3PR.cca,display=c("sp","wa","lc","bp","cn"))
 
nmds_df<-scores(otus_1e3PR.cca,display=c("sites"))

#Check the attributes

attributes(scrs)
## $names
## [1] "species"     "sites"       "constraints" "biplot"      "centroids"
#Extract site data first

df_sites <- data.frame(cbind(scrs$sites,pH=env_1e3$pH))

p<-ggplot(data=df_sites,aes(CCA1,CCA2,colour=pH)) + geom_point(size=3) + sc + theme_bw()

No we biplot on the environmental variables:

multiplier <- vegan:::ordiArrowMul(scrs$biplot)

Reference: http://www.inside-r.org/packages/cran/vegan/docs/envfit

The printed output of continuous variables (vectors) gives the direction cosines which are the coordinates of the heads of unit length vectors. In plot these are scaled by their correlation (square root of the column r2) so that weak predictors have shorter arrows than strong predictors. You can see the scaled relative lengths using command scores. The plotted (and scaled) arrows are further adjusted to the current graph using a constant multiplier: this will keep the relative r2-scaled lengths of the arrows but tries to fill the current plot. You can see the multiplier using vegan:::ordiArrowMul(result_of_envfit), and set it with the argument arrow.mul.

df_arrows<- scrs$biplot*multiplier
colnames(df_arrows)<-c("x","y")
df_arrows=as.data.frame(df_arrows)
 
p<-p+geom_segment(data=df_arrows, aes(x = 0, y = 0, xend = x, yend = y),
                 arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.2, "cm")),color="#808080",alpha=0.75)
 
p<-p+geom_text(data=as.data.frame(df_arrows*1.1),aes(x, y, label = rownames(df_arrows)),color="#808080",alpha=0.75)

plot(p)

Mantel tests are another ordination free method of linking environment and community structure:

envN <- env_1e3[,1:6]

envN.dist <- vegdist(scale(envN), "euclid")

otus_1e3P.dist <- vegdist(otus_1e3P,method="bray")

mantel(otus_1e3P.dist,envN.dist)
## 
## Mantel statistic based on Pearson's product-moment correlation 
## 
## Call:
## mantel(xdis = otus_1e3P.dist, ydis = envN.dist) 
## 
## Mantel statistic r: 0.3992 
##       Significance: 0.001 
##

##    90%    95%  97.5%    99% 
## 0.0949 0.1228 0.1424 0.1529 
## Permutation: free
## Number of permutations: 999

Differential OTU abundance across samples

We are now going to read in the Crohns disease study data from our earlier tutorial:

otus <- read.csv("otus.csv",header=TRUE,row.names=1)
meta <- read.csv("meta.csv",header=TRUE,row.names=1)

We begin by subsetting the data and meta data files to just the control samples and those from the beginning of EEN treatment:

meta_CDH <- subset(meta,meta$Sample == "A")
otus_CDH <- subset(otus,meta$Sample == "A")

and filtering out samples with less than 10,000 reads.

otus_CDH_1e4 <- otus_CDH[rowSums(otus_CDH)>1e4,]
meta_CDH_1e4 <- meta_CDH[rownames(otus_CDH_1e4),]

Now we add pseud-count, calculate proportions and log-transform:

otus_CDH_1e4 <- otus_CDH_1e4[,colSums(otus_CDH_1e4) > 0]
otus_CDHP <- otus_CDH_1e4/rowSums(otus_CDH_1e4)
otus_CDH1 <- otus_CDH_1e4 + 1
otus_CDH_logP <- log(otus_CDH1/rowSums(otus_CDH1))

We will show all the code here but normally you might put this in a little function:

nT <- ncol(otus_CDH_logP)
p <- rep(0,nT)
chi <- rep(0,nT)

meanH <- rep(0,nT)
meanCD <- rep(0,nT)

for(i in 1:nT){
    temp <- kruskal.test(otus_CDH_logP[,i] ~ meta_CDH_1e4$Type)
  tmean <- aggregate(otus_CDHP[,i]~meta_CDH_1e4$Type, FUN=mean)
    chi[i] <- temp$statistic
    p[i] <- temp$p.value
    meanCD[i] <- tmean[[2]][1]
    meanH[i] <- tmean[[2]][2]
}

Now we use Benjamini-Hochberg correction and group results back into data frame:

pa <- p.adjust(p, method = "BH") 
sig.df <- data.frame(chi,p,pa,meanH,meanCD)
rownames(sig.df) <- colnames(otus_CDH_logP)

Look at top ten most significant OTUs

sig10 <- head(sig.df[order(sig.df$p),],10)

Plot these as boxplots:

otus_CDHP_sig10 <- (t(otus_CDH_logP)[rownames(sig10),])/log(10)

melt_sig10 <- melt(otus_CDHP_sig10)
colnames(melt_sig10) <- c("Taxa","Sample","Abundance")

type_sig10 <- factor(rep("CD",nrow(melt_sig10)),levels=c("CD","H"))
 
i=1
for (samplei in melt_sig10$Sample){
  type_sig10[i] <- meta_CDH_1e4[samplei,]$Type
  i=i+1
}

melt_sig10$Type <- type_sig10

p<-ggplot(melt_sig10,aes(Type,Abundance,colour=Type))+ylab("Relative abundance")
p<-p+geom_boxplot()+geom_jitter()+theme_bw()+
  facet_wrap( ~ Taxa , scales="free", ncol=3)
p<-p+theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1,vjust=0.5))

plot(p)

#We will convert our table to DESeqDataSet object
otus_CDH0 <- otus_CDH_1e4[,colSums(otus_CDH_1e4) > 0]

countData = round(as(otus_CDH0, "matrix"), digits = 0)

countData<-t(countData) 
 
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData, meta_CDH_1e4, as.formula(~ Type))
## converting counts to integer mode
dds <- estimateSizeFactors(dds)
dds <- estimateDispersions(dds)
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
plotDispEsts(dds, main="DESeq: Per-gene dispersion estimates")

data_deseq_test = DESeq(dds)
## using pre-existing size factors
## estimating dispersions
## found already estimated dispersions, replacing these
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
## -- replacing outliers and refitting for 563 genes
## -- DESeq argument 'minReplicatesForReplace' = 7 
## -- original counts are preserved in counts(dds)
## estimating dispersions
## fitting model and testing
## Extract the results
res = results(data_deseq_test, cooksCutoff = FALSE)
res_tax = cbind(as.data.frame(res), as.matrix(countData[rownames(res), ]), OTU = rownames(res))
 
sig = 0.001
fold = 0
plot.point.size = 2
label=T
tax.display = NULL
tax.aggregate = "OTU"
 
res_tax_sig = subset(res_tax, padj < sig & fold < abs(log2FoldChange))
 
res_tax_sig <- res_tax_sig[order(res_tax_sig$padj),]
 
## Plot the data
### MA plot
res_tax$Significant <- ifelse(rownames(res_tax) %in% rownames(res_tax_sig) , "Yes", "No")
res_tax$Significant[is.na(res_tax$Significant)] <- "No"
p1 <- ggplot(data = res_tax, aes(x = baseMean, y = log2FoldChange, color = Significant)) +
  geom_point(size = plot.point.size) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("black", "red")) +
  labs(x = "Mean abundance", y = "Log2 fold change")+theme_bw()

rlab <- data.frame(res_tax,Display=res_tax[,"OTU"])

p1 <- p1 + geom_text(data = subset(rlab, Significant == "Yes"), aes(label = Display), size = 2, vjust = 1)

plot(p1)
